<paper id="1498125516"><title>Verifying Continuous Time Markov Chains</title><year>1996</year><authors><author org="ECE, UT Austin" id="2917461269">Adnan Aziz</author><author org="Bell Labs., AT&amp;T" id="2241879559">Kumud Sanwal</author><author org="CBL Cadence" id="2095411425">Vigyan Singhal</author><author org="EECS, UC Berkeley,#TAB#" id="2038038819">Robert K. Brayton</author></authors><n_citation>290</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>2005998857</reference><reference>2153439859</reference><reference>2168605507</reference></references><venue id="1162450063" type="C">Computer Aided Verification</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-61474-5_75</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.62908">Markov chain mixing time</keyword><keyword weight="0.62135">Markov process</keyword><keyword weight="0.63078">Markov property</keyword><keyword weight="0.45161">Algebra</keyword><keyword weight="0.41409">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.60632">Uniformization (probability theory)</keyword><keyword weight="0.64898">Markov chain</keyword><keyword weight="0.44372">Algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.63793">Balance equation</keyword><keyword weight="0.61377">Markov kernel</keyword><keyword weight="0.68246">Examples of Markov chains</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We present a logical formalism for expressing properties of continuous time Markov chains. The semantics for such properties arise as a natural extension of previous work on discrete time Markov chains to continuous time. The major result is that the verification problem is decidable; this is shown using results in algebraic and transcendental number theory.</abstract></paper>